[Cyanide exists in several forms. While it is easy to remember it is a
colorless, odorless gas, it is also available in crystalline form as
potassium cyanide and sodium cyanide. These are generally the forms
that are used in food, as this case appears to be. Consequently, a
person may be exposed through inhalation or ingestion or through
absorption through the skin on contact.

Cyanide is used in manufacturing for making paper, textiles, and
plastics. It is also in photographic developing chemicals, which may
not be in great demand but are still around. Metallurgy employs
cyanide salts for electroplating, metal cleaning, and removing gold
from its ore. Cyanide gas is used to exterminate pests in ships and
buildings. Cyanide is also found in chemicals, such as
acetonitril-based products which may be used to remove artificial
nails, or perhaps polish. Sadly this is sometimes ingested.

People exposed to a small amount of cyanide by inhalation, absorption,
or ingestion may have some or all of the following symptoms within
minutes: rapid breathing, restlessness, dizziness, weakness, headache,
nausea and vomiting, and rapid heart rate. Exposure to a large amount
of cyanide by any route may cause any of the following symptoms:
convulsions, low blood pressure, slow heart rate, loss of
consciousness, lung injury, and respiratory failure leading to death.

Generally treatment for cyanide poisoning must be given very swiftly,
especially after ingestion. Unfortunately specific antidotes and are
generally only available at a hospital. Hyperbaric oxygen therapy
chambers have proven to be helpful. - Mod.TG

